:0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/leptos-rs/cargo-leptos/issues/470/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"completed","pinned_comment":null,"score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/issues/592","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/issues/592/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/issues/592/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/issues/592/events","html_url":"https://github.com/madmax983/autumn/issues/592","id":4368004368,"node_id":"I_kwDORsxAfc8AAAABBFp1EA","number":592,"title":"Certify examples as runnable user journeys","user":{"login":"madmax983","id":1848860,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjE4NDg4NjA=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1848860?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983","html_url":"https://github.com/madmax983","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"labels":[{"id":10798315812,"node_id":"LA_kwDORsxAfc8AAAACg6E5JA","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/labels/spec","name":"spec","color":"0e8a16","default":false,"description":"PM specification awaiting engineering"},{"id":10798315907,"node_id":"LA_kwDORsxAfc8AAAACg6E5gw","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/labels/pm","name":"pm","color":"fbca04","default":false,"description":"Authored by Vantage / product management"}],"state":"closed","locked":false,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":0,"created_at":"2026-05-02T05:06:26Z","updated_at":"2026-05-10T03:08:34Z","closed_at":"2026-05-10T03:08:34Z","assignee":null,"author_association":"OWNER","active_lock_reason":null,"sub_issues_summary":{"total":0,"completed":0,"percent_completed":0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"## Problem (the \"So What?\")\nAutumn's examples are the proof that the framework can ship real applications, not just expose clever primitives. Today the README, workspace membership, docs, and `examples/` directory can drift: for example, `examples/canopy` exists locally but is not listed in the workspace or README example table. That ambiguity turns examples from adoption assets into trust debt, especially for evaluators comparing Autumn against Rails/Phoenix/Loco where the guided app path is part of the product.\n\n## User Story\nAs a framework user evaluating Autumn, I want every advertised example to be clearly cataloged, runnable, and tied to a specific user journey, so that I can pick the closest starting point and prove the framework works without spelunking source folders or guessing which examples are blessed.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A single documented examples catalog lists every supported example with its target persona, demonstrated journey, key Autumn capabilities, prerequisites, exact run command, and expected first successful request or page.\n- [ ] Every example advertised in `README.md`, `docs/guide/*`, or the tutorial appears in the catalog with the same name and purpose.\n- [ ] Every cataloged example is either a workspace member that participates in the normal example validation path, or is explicitly marked as external/manual with a reason and a documented smoke command.\n- [ ] Every directory under `examples/` is either cataloged as supported or explicitly marked experimental/scratch/excluded with a short rationale; unmarked orphan directories fail the documented release check.\n- [ ] Each supported example has a README quickstart from clean checkout to first successful request, including required services such as Postgres or Redis and the exact command that proves success.\n- [ ] The release checklist includes a machine-checkable example drift gate that catches README/catalog/workspace mismatches before publishing `autumn-web` or `autumn-cli`.\n- [ ] The validation output groups examples by support tier, so a contributor can immediately see which failures block release and which are intentionally manual.\n- [ ] The catalog maps current examples to distinct journeys rather than repeating the same CRUD story: first route, CRUD app, admin/static rendering, profiles/tasks, distributed deployment, hooks/revisions, full-stack reddit clone, custom config loading, and WebSocket echo.\n- [ ] Generated artifacts such as compiled CSS are not treated as source-of-truth for the catalog; example status is owned by docs and validation metadata.\n- [ ] This adds no new public `autumn-web` API and does not require downstream app migration.\n\n## Success Metric\nA new evaluator can choose the right supported example and reach its documented first successful request in under **3 minutes** after prerequisites are running. The release drift gate catches **100%** of unlisted `examples/` directories and README/catalog/workspace mismatches before a release is cut.\n\n## Out of Scope\n- Adding a new showcase application.\n- Rewriting existing examples to demonstrate new framework features.\n- Browser end-to-end testing or screenshot regression testing.\n- The canonical downstream app integration testing story; #513 owns that.\n- Generated auth, admin adapters, jobs dashboards, or plugin conformance; #588, #590, #585, and #591 own those product surfaces.\n- Changing the published `autumn-web` API or crate layout.\n\n## Gap Analysis\n- **axum** — the official repo positions axum as an ergonomic, modular library and points users at examples and community showcases, but it does not need a certified app-journey catalog because axum is not promising a batteries-included app framework: https://github.com/tokio-rs/axum.\n- **actix-web** — Actix has a large community examples repository, which is useful breadth, but it reads like ecosystem samples rather than a curated framework adoption path: https://github.com/actix/examples.\n- **rocket** — Rocket's guide is strong as a tutorial/reference, but Rocket does not currently compete on a Rails-style catalog of runnable full-stack example journeys: https://rocket.rs/guide.\n- **loco.rs** — Loco is the closest Rust peer: starters, generated commands, routes, doctor, testing docs, and template choices make the app journey explicit. Autumn has richer server-rendered examples, but without catalog certification the advantage is harder for users to see: https://loco.rs/docs/getting-started/starters/.\n- **leptos** — Leptos has starter templates and examples for full-stack/SSR/CSR Rust UI apps, but its examples serve a different product promise: reactive UI and hydration rather than Autumn's server-first Rails/Spring shape: https://github.com/leptos-rs.\n- **Rails** — Rails' getting-started guide creates a concrete blog app and teaches the app shape as the canonical adoption path. Autumn's examples should play the same role, but with multiple certified journeys instead of one tutorial app: https://guides.rubyonrails.org/getting_started.html.\n- **Phoenix** — Phoenix generated apps and resources come with tests and real examples, which makes the generated journey self-verifying. Autumn should copy the product principle, not the implementation: every blessed example should prove its journey still runs: https://hexdocs.pm/phoenix/testing.html.\n- **Django** — Django's tutorial series carries the example through tests and reusable-app packaging, reinforcing that examples are maintained teaching artifacts, not throwaway folders: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/intro/reusable-apps/.\n- **The autumn-shaped answer** — treat examples as part of the product surface. A supported example is a promise: documented purpose, exact run path, known prerequisites, drift checks, and a clear support tier. If an example is scratch work, mark it as such or keep it out of the adoption path.\n\n## Complexity Tier\nM — touches documentation, release validation, and example metadata across the workspace; no public API impact and no downstream migration burden, but multi-service examples make the validation matrix more than a one-file cleanup.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/issues/592/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/issues/592/timeline","performed_via_github_app":{"id":1144995,"client_id":"Iv23liVemv8A9if9v0F2","slug":"chatgpt-codex-connector","node_id":"A_kwHOAOQ6Gs4AEXij","owner":{"login":"openai","id":14957082,"node_id":"MDEyOk9yZ2FuaXphdGlvbjE0OTU3MDgy","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/14957082?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai","html_url":"https://github.com/openai","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/events{/pr